KINDERFEINDLICHKEIT : is 'borrowed' from German in the absence of a word having the same meaning in English. When Germans use it they mean State/official/institutionalised hostility or coldness towards children.

Usage : in English it used for example as an attributor of characteristic(s) to :

a) that aspect of English tort law that denies children protection in law from misfeasant/malfeasant conduct of public offices;

b) political acts like that of Thatcher when as Education minister she cancelled school milk for children;

c) the Blair "war" on alienated developmentally mutilated children - a society in which the good citizen is a gluttonous consumer and part-time parent - the "Brown" economy that promotes part-time parenting.

